# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akvavit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:akvavit/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:akvavit/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:akvavit/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:akvavit/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:akvavit/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:akvavit/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:akvavit/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:akvavit/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:akvavit/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:akvavit/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:akvavit/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:akvavit/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:akvavit/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:akvavit/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:akvavit/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:akvavit/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:akvavit/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:akvavit/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:akvavit/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:akvavit/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:akvavit/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:akvavit/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:akvavit/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:akvavit/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:akvavit/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:akvavit/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:akvavit/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:akvavit/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:akvavit/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:akvavit/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:akvavit/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:akvavit/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:akvavit/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:akvavit/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:akvavit/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:akvavit/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:akvavit/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:akvavit/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:akvavit/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:akvavit/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:akvavit/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:akvavit/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:akvavit/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:akvavit/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:akvavit/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:akvavit/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:akvavit/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:akvavit/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:akvavit/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:akvavit/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:akvavit/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:akvavit/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:akvavit/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:akvavit/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:akvavit/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:akvavit/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:akvavit/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:akvavit/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:akvavit/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:akvavit/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:akvavit/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:akvavit/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:akvavit/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:akvavit/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:akvavit/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:akvavit/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:akvavit/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:akvavit/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:akvavit/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:akvavit/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:akvavit/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:akvavit/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:akvavit/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:akvavit/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:akvavit/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:akvavit/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:akvavit/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:akvavit/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:akvavit/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:akvavit/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:akvavit/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:akvavit/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] The word is a compound of the Iberian languages' words for 'water' (*agua* in Castilian, i.e.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Spanish; *aigua* in Catalan; *água* in Portuguese; *auga* in Galician) and 'burning'/'fiery' (*ardiente* in Castilian; *ardent* in Catalan; *ardente* in Portuguese and Galician).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] A comparable word in English is "firewater", though the English term is colloquial or humorous, whereas *aguardiente* is stylistically neutral in Spanish.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] However, *aguardiente* and *aguardente* are not legal denominations.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Instead, different categories of *aguardientes* (spirits in the English version) are established according to raw materials.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In the Spanish version, wine spirit (brandy) is *aguardiente de vino*, fruit spirit is *aguardiente de fruta*, grain spirit (other than whiskey and neutral grain spirit) is *aguardiente de cereales*, etc.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Some drinks named *aguardiente* or similar are of different origins (grape pomace, sugarcane); other drinks with the same origin may have different names (clairin, brandy).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Brazil, a beverage known as *cachaça* or *pinga*, considered distinct from traditional *aguardiente*, is made from sugarcane.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Cachaça* has two varieties: unaged (white) and aged (gold).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] White *cachaça* is usually bottled immediately after distillation and tends to be cheaper.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is often used to prepare caipirinha and other beverages in which *cachaça* is an ingredient.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Dark *cachaça*, usually seen as the "premium" variety, is aged in wood barrels and is meant to be drunk neat.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Traditionally, no herbs are used to flavor the *cachaça*; its flavor is influenced by the fermentation agent, time spent in the cask, or the type of wood from which the barrel is made.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] One form that can be qualified as moonshine is known as "Maria Louca" ("Crazy Mary").
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] This is *aguardiente*, made in jails by inmates.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It can be made from many cereals, ranging from beans to rice, or whatever can be converted into alcohol, be it fruit peels or candy, using improvised and illegal equipment.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Grogue, also known as grogu or grogo (derived from English grog), is a Cape Verdean alcoholic beverage, an *aguardiente* made from sugarcane processed in a trapiche.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Its production is fundamentally artisanal, and nearly all the sugarcane is used in producing grogue.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Chile, *aguardiente* is an alcoholic beverage of 45% and higher ABV (beverages with over 55% ABV are illegal).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is made, like Italian grappa, by distilling the grape residue, primarily the skins and pulp (**hollejo**) plus the stems (**escobajos**) and seeds, left over from winemaking after pressing the grapes.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is used to make several other flavored liquors, such as the *murtado* or **enmurtillado** (using sun-dried *murtilla*, an orange-reddish wild rose fruit), the **enguindado** (soaking sun-dried morello cherries) and *licor de oro* (flavored with saffron and lemon peel).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Dried mint, peeled walnuts, almonds, and other aromatic herbs are also used to flavor the *aguardiente*.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is mainly consumed by itself or as a base to make *cola de mono* ("monkey tail").
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Colombia, *aguardiente* is an anise-flavored liqueur derived from sugarcane, popular in the Andean region.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Different flavors are obtained by adding different amounts of aniseed, leading to extensive marketing and fierce competition between brands.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Aguardiente* has 24%–29% alcohol content.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Other anise-flavored liqueurs similar to *aguardiente*, but with a lower alcohol content, are also sold.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Since the Spanish era, *aguardiente* has maintained the status of the most popular alcoholic beverage in the Andean regions of Colombia, with the notable exception of the Caribbean region, where rum is most popular.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Generally, *aguardiente* is rarely drunk in cocktails and usually drunk neat.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] On the Caribbean coast, there is a moonshine called "Cococho", an *aguardiente* infamous for the number of blindness cases due to the addition of methanol.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Costa Rica, it is 30% alcohol, with a neutral flavor.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] The Costa Rican government tightly controls Guaro to help prevent clandestine production.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Guam and the Mariana Islands, a distilled version of *tubâ* (coconut palm wine introduced from the Philippines) is known as *aguajente* (also *aguayente* or *agi*).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It was prevalent among the Chamorro people, but is largely extinct; the United States banned its manufacture soon after the acquisition of Guam from the Spanish Empire in 1899.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] A local company "Aguayente distillers" has recently installed a commercial still and will soon start distilling liquor from locally grown potatoes.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is also derived from sugar cane, but unlike Colombia, it is left largely unflavoured.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is then taken straight as shots, mulled with cinnamon (*canela* in Spanish) and fruit juices to make the hot cocktail *canelazo*, or mixed with the juice of naranjilla and spices for the hot cocktail *draquita*.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Locally or artisanally made *aguardiente* is commonly called *punta*, "puro" or *trago*, and alcohol content can vary widely, from "mild" *puntas* of about 10% to "strong" of about 40% or higher.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] The traditional distillation process produces *aguardiente* as strong as 60 g/L.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Every Ecuadorian province has a slightly different flavor to the *aguardiente* made there, and each province has a different recipe for *canelazo*.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is the most commonly consumed strong alcohol.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Mexico, *aguardiente* goes by many names, including *habanero*.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In the state of Michoacán, *charanda* is a traditional rum-like sugar cane *aguardiente*.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Casa Berreteaga marketed an *aguardiente* called "Berreteaga", which used sugarcane sourced from the Coxcatlan region of Puebla.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Berreteaga was a fortified wine made from rum and sweet wine (usually Muscat) or (uncommonly) a sweet brandy that was then aged in oak barrels.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Portuguese *aguardente* has several varieties.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Aguardente vínica* is distilled from either good quality or undrinkable wine.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is mostly used to fortify wines such as port or aged to make *aguardente velha* (old burning water), a kind of brandy.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Aguardente bagaceira* (mostly known as "bagaço") is made from pomace to prevent waste after the close of wine season.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is usually bootlegged, as most drinkers only appreciate it in its traditional formulation of 50% to 80% ABV.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] A common way to drink it is as *café com cheirinho* ("coffee with a little scent"), a liqueur coffee made with espresso.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In the Azores, this *espresso-aguardente* combination is commonly referred to as *café com música* ("coffee with music").
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Aguardente Medronho* is a variety distilled from the fruit of the *Arbutus unedo* tree.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In Madeira, it is the core ingredient for *poncha*, a beverage around which a festival is based.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Most of the *aguardente* from the region is made from sugarcane.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In certain areas of the Pyrenees in Catalonia, *aiguardent*, as it is known in Catalan, is used as an essential ingredient in the preparation of *tupí*, a type of cheese.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Galicia is renowned for the quality and variety of its *augardentes* (Galician), or *aguardientes* (Spanish), including *augardente de bagazo* (*aguardiente de Orujo*), which is obtained from the distillation of the pomace of grapes, and is clear and colorless.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It typically contains over 50% alcohol, sometimes significantly more, and is still made traditionally in many villages across Galicia today.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Augardente de herbas*, usually yellow, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo* and herbs (*herbas*), with chamomile being a substantial ingredient.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Licor café* (typical distilled drink in the province of Ourense), black in color, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo*, coffee (*café*), and sugar.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] *Crema de augardente* or c*rema de caña* is a cream liqueur based on *augardente*, coffee, cream, milk, and other ingredients.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] In some places in Galicia, a small glass is traditionally taken at breakfast as a tonic before a hard day's work on the land.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] The word "*orujo*" is Spanish and not Galician, but is used to distinguish Galician and some Spanish augardentes from those of other countries.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Most of the moonshine in Spain is made as a byproduct of winemaking by distilling the squeezed skins of the grapes.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] The essential product is called "*orujo*" or "*aguardiente*" (burning water).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] The homemade versions are usually more potent and have a higher alcoholic content, well over the 40% that the commercial versions typically have.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It is often mixed with herbs, spices, fruits, or other distillates.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] Types include *pacharán*, *licor de café* and *orujo de hierbas* (tea mixed with orujo).
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] During the mission and rancho periods of California history, *aguardiente* was made out of mission grapes.
[src:akvavit/aguardiente] It was popular during the Gold Rush of 1849.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The word *aquavit* derives from the Latin *aqua vitae*, "water of life." Compare the words *whisky* and *whiskey*, from Gaelic *uisce beatha*, which has the same meaning.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Likewise, clear fruit brandy is called *eau de vie* (French for "water of life").
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Akvavit is an important part of Nordic drinking culture, where it is often drunk during festive gatherings, such as Christmas dinners and the Midsummer celebration, and as an aperitif.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Iceland, Sweden, Denmark, and Germany, aquavit is chilled and often drunk in a single gulp from a small shot glass.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] This is usually attributed to tradition.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Norway, it is not generally chilled, but enjoyed slowly.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Sweden, aquavit is commonly consumed immediately following a song, called a snapsvisa.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The most well-known song is "Helan Går".
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Finland and Sweden, aquavit consumed from a shot glass is also commonly associated with crayfish parties, which are traditionally held during late August.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Denmark, aquavit is called snaps or akvavit, and is primarily consumed in December during Christmas lunches or around Easter during Easter lunches.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] It is consumed year-round, though, mainly for lunches of traditional Danish dishes where beer is also always on the table.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Norway, where most aquavit is matured in oak casks, the drink is served at room temperature in tulip-shaped glasses.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Aquavit arguably complements beer well, and its consumption is very often preceded by a swig of beer.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Akvavit must be distilled from an agricultural base, most commonly grain or potatoes.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Similarly to gin, it is flavoured with botanicals.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The dominant flavours must be caraway or dill, or sometimes both.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Swedish Akvavit must also contain fennel in order to be labelled as such.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Other common botanicals include cardamom, cumin, anise, and coriander.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The Danish distillery Aalborg makes an akvavit distilled with amber, which imparts a pine-like citrusy note.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The Aalborg brand is now produced in Norway by Arcus Group.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The recipes and flavours differ between brands, with each brand's unique characteristics coming from distillation methods and supporting botanicals in their blends.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Un-aged Akvavit is clear, while aged Akvavit typically has a pale straw-to-golden hue, depending on how long it has been aged in oak casks (most common in Norway) or the amount of colourant used.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Normally, a darker colour suggests a higher age or the use of young casks, although artificial caramel colouring and infusing fruits or botanicals for colour and flavour are permitted before bottling.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Clear akvavit is often called *taffel*, meaning table aquavit.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Taffel aquavit is typically aged in old casks that do not colour the finished spirit, or it is not aged at all.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The earliest known reference to "aquavit" is found in a 1531 letter from the Lord of Bergenshus castle, (Norway) Eske Bille, to Olav Engelbrektsson, the last Roman Catholic Archbishop of Norway.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The letter, dated April 13 and accompanying a package, offers the archbishop "some water which is called Aqua Vite and is a help for all sort of illness which a man can have both internally and externally".
[src:akvavit/akvavit] While this claim for the medicinal properties of the drink may be rather inflated, aquavit is popularly believed to ease the digestion of rich foods.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Norway, it is drunk at celebrations, particularly Christmas, Easter, or May 17 (Norwegian Constitution Day).
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Denmark, it is traditionally associated with Christmas and Easter lunches.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In Sweden, it is a staple of the traditional midsummer celebrations dinner, usually drunk while singing one of many drinking songs.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] It is usually drunk as snaps during meals, especially during the appetizer course — along with pickled herring, crayfish, lutefisk, or smoked fish.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] In this regard, it is popularly quipped that aquavit helps the fish swim down to the stomach.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] It is also a regular in traditional Norwegian Christmas meals, including roasted rib of pork and rib of lamb (*pinnekjøtt*).
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The spices and the alcohol are said to help digest the meal, which is very rich in fat.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Among the most important brands are Løiten, Lysholm, Opland, and Simers from Norway; Aalborg and Brøndum from Denmark; and O.P.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] While the Danish and Swedish variants are normally very light in colour, most of the Norwegian brands are matured in oak casks for at least six months, and for some brands even as long as 12 years, making them generally darker in colour.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] While members of all three nations can be found to claim that "their" style of aquavit is the best as a matter of national pride, Swedish *akvavit* is typically the most renowned around the world, specifically so in the culinary scene.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Whilst the Norwegian *akevitt* tends to have if not the most distinctive character, then at least the most overpowering flavour and deepest colour due to the aging process.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Peculiar to the Norwegian tradition are *Linje Aquavits* (such as "Løiten Linie" and "Lysholm Linie").
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Linje Aquavit is named after the tradition of sending oak barrels of aquavit with ships from Norway to Australia and back again, thereby passing the equator ("linje") twice before being bottled.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The constant movement, high humidity, and fluctuating temperature cause the spirit to extract more flavour and contribute to accelerated maturation.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Norwegian aquavit distillers Anora (formerly Arcus) carried out a test where they tried to emulate the rocking of the casks aboard the "Linje" ships while the oak barrels were subjected to the weather elements, as they would aboard a ship.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The finished product was, according to Anora, far from the taste that a proper *linje* aquavit should have.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Therefore, to this day, boats loaded with "Linie Aquavit" set sail from Norway to Australia and back again before they are bottled and sold as part of the Norwegian Christmas traditions, but also enjoyed all year round.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Aquavit was seldom produced outside of the Nordic countries, but that began to change dramatically starting around 2010, especially in the United States, and particularly in areas that have larger concentrations of people with a Nordic heritage.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] An exception, however, is Northern Germany, and in particular the German state of Schleswig-Holstein, which was part of Denmark until the 19th century (see History of Schleswig-Holstein) and still has a notable Danish minority.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Among the most important German brands are Bommerlunder from Flensburg, Kieler Sprotte from Kiel, and Malteserkreuz.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Malteserkreuz has been produced in Berlin since 1924 by a subsidiary of Sweden's Vin & Sprit AB (now Pernod Ricard), the producer of many Swedish akvavits, and can be considered a German imitation of the Nordic aquavits since it is based on an original Danish recipe.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Brands from Schleswig-Holstein, however, often have a long history, comparable to their Nordic counterparts.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Bommerlunder, for instance, has been made since 1760.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Aquavit is also an important part of the traditional cuisine of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] German aquavit is virtually always distilled from fermented grain and generally has an alcohol content of 38% by volume, marginally less than Scandinavian aquavits.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Many distilleries in the United States produce aquavit, especially in parts of the country with high populations of people of Nordic heritage.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Examples include Colorado, Minnesota, Michigan, Wisconsin, Montana, Illinois, Oregon, New Hampshire, and Washington.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] The Midwest states in particular do quite well for the category and have produced numerous internationally acclaimed/award-winning brands.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] See List of Akvavit Producers in the United States for brand names and distilleries.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Aquavit is also seeing a rise in popularity in Canada, particularly in Scandinavian settlements.
[src:akvavit/akvavit] Notable brands include Spirit of York Co in Toronto, Ontario, Drum Distilling Co in Drumheller, Alberta, and The Newfoundland Distillery Co, in Clarkes Beach Newfoundland.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta's economy is advanced, open, market-based, and characterized by a highly educated workforce, strong institutions and property rights, and sophisticated financial markets.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The service sector employs 80% of Albertans, in fields like healthcare, education, professional services, retail, tourism and financial services.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The industrial base includes manufacturing, construction, and agriculture (10%, 5%, and 2% of employment respectively), while the knowledge economy includes about 3000 tech companies employing an estimated 60,000 people, mainly in Calgary and Edmonton.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The energy sector employs 5% of Albertans but significantly impacts exports and GDP.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta's exports, primarily US-bound, consist of 70% oil and gas, 13% food products, and 12% industrial products.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Oil and gas are culturally influential, having shaped politics, generated "striking it rich" narratives, and created boom-and-bust cycles.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 2023, Alberta's output was $350 billion, 15% of Canada's GDP.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Until the 1930s, Alberta's political landscape consisted of two major parties: the centre-left Liberals and the agrarian United Farmers of Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Today, Alberta is generally perceived as a conservative province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The right-wing Social Credit Party held office continually from 1935 to 1971 before the centre-right Progressive Conservatives held office continually from 1971 to 2015, the latter being the longest unbroken run in government at the provincial or federal level in Canadian history.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The United Conservative Party has held office since 2019.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Since before it became part of Canada, Alberta has been home to several First Nations, such as Plains Indians and Woodland Cree.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] It was historically also a territory used by fur traders of the rival companies Hudson's Bay Company and North West Company.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Dominion of Canada bought the lands that would become Alberta as part of the NWT in 1870.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] From the late 1800s to the early 1900s, many immigrants arrived in an effort to prevent the prairies from being annexed by the United States.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Growing wheat and cattle ranching became very profitable during this period.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 1905, the Alberta Act was passed, creating the province of Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Massive oil reserves were discovered in 1947.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The exploitation of oil sands began in 1967.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta is renowned for its natural beauty and is home to important nature reserves.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] It is also well known as a rich source of fossils.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] It is home to six UNESCO-designated World Heritage Sites: the Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, Dinosaur Provincial Park, Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump, Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park, Wood Buffalo National Park and Writing-on-Stone Provincial Park.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Other popular sites include Banff National Park, Elk Island National Park, Jasper National Park, Waterton Lakes National Park, and Drumheller.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta was named after Princess Louise Caroline Alberta (1848–1939), the fourth daughter of Queen Victoria.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Princess Louise was the wife of John Campbell, Marquess of Lorne, Governor General of Canada (1878–83).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Lake Louise and Mount Alberta were also named in her honour.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The name "Alberta" is a feminine Latinized form of Albert, the name of Princess Louise's father, the Prince Consort (cf.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Medieval Latin: *Albertus*, masculine) and its Germanic cognates, ultimately derived from the Proto-Germanic language **Aþalaberhtaz* (compound of "noble" + "bright/famous").
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta, with an area of 661,848 km2 (255,541 sq mi), is the fourth-largest province after Quebec, Ontario, and British Columbia.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta's southern border is the 49th parallel north, which separates it from the U.S. state of Montana.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The 60th parallel north divides Alberta from the Northwest Territories.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The province extends 1,223 kilometres (760 mi) north to south and 660 km (410 mi) east to west at its maximum width.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Its highest point is 3,747 metres (12,293 ft) at the summit of Mount Columbia in the Rocky Mountains along the southwest border while its lowest point is 152 m (499 ft) on the Slave River in Wood Buffalo National Park in the northeast.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] With the exception of the semi-arid climate of the steppe in the south-eastern section, the province has adequate water resources.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] There are numerous rivers and lakes in Alberta used for swimming, fishing and a range of water sports.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] There are three large lakes, Lake Claire (1,436 km2 [554 sq mi]) in Wood Buffalo National Park, Lesser Slave Lake (1,168 km2 or 451 sq mi), and Lake Athabasca (7,898 km2 or 3,049 sq mi), which lies in both Alberta and Saskatchewan.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The longest river in the province is the Athabasca River, which travels 1,538 km (956 mi) from the Columbia Icefield in the Rocky Mountains to Lake Athabasca.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The largest river is the Peace River with an average flow of 2,100 cubic metres per second (74,000 cu ft/s).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Peace River originates in the Rocky Mountains of northern British Columbia and flows through northern Alberta and into the Slave River, a tributary of the Mackenzie River.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta's capital city, Edmonton, is located roughly at the geographic centre of the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] It is the most northerly major city in Canada and serves as a gateway and hub for resource development in northern Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] With its proximity to Canada's largest oil fields, the region has most of western Canada's oil refinery capacity.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Calgary is about 280 km (170 mi) south of Edmonton and 240 km (150 mi) north of Montana by highway, surrounded by extensive ranching country.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Almost 75% of the province's population lives in the Calgary–Edmonton Corridor.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The land grant policy to the railways served as a means to populate the province in its early years.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Most of the northern half of the province is boreal forest, while the Rocky Mountains along the southwestern boundary are largely temperate coniferous forests of the Alberta Mountain forests and Alberta–British Columbia foothills forests.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The southern quarter of the province is prairie, ranging from shortgrass prairie in the southeastern corner to mixed grass prairie in an arc to the west and north of it.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The central aspen parkland region extending in a broad arc between the prairies and the forests, from Calgary, north to Edmonton, and then east to Lloydminster, contains the most fertile soil in the province and most of the population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Much of the unforested part of Alberta is given over either to grain farming or cattle ranching, with mixed farming more common in the north and centre, while ranching and irrigated agriculture predominate in the south.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Alberta badlands are in southeastern Alberta, where the Red Deer River crosses the flat prairie and farmland, and features deep canyons and striking landforms.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Dinosaur Provincial Park, near Brooks, showcases the badlands terrain, desert flora, and remnants from Alberta's past when dinosaurs roamed the then lush landscape.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta extends for over 1,200 km (750 mi) from north to south; its climate, therefore, varies considerably.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Average high temperatures in January range from 0 °C (32 °F) in the southwest to −24 °C (−11 °F) in the far north.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The northerly location and isolation from the weather systems of the Pacific Ocean cause Alberta to have a dry climate with little moderation from the ocean.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Annual precipitation ranges from 300 millimetres (12 in) in the southeast to 450 mm (18 in) in the north, except in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains where total precipitation including snowfall can reach 600 mm (24 in) annually.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Northern Alberta is mostly covered by boreal forest and has a subarctic climate.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The agricultural area of southern Alberta has a semi-arid steppe climate because the annual precipitation is less than the water that evaporates or is used by plants.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The southeastern corner of Alberta, part of the Palliser Triangle, experiences greater summer heat and lower rainfall than the rest of the province, and as a result, suffers frequent crop yield problems and occasional severe droughts.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Western Alberta is protected by the mountains and enjoys the mild temperatures brought by winter Chinook winds.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Central and parts of northwestern Alberta in the Peace River region are largely aspen parkland, a biome transitional between prairie to the south and boreal forest to the north.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta has a humid continental climate with warm summers and cold winters.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The province is open to cold Arctic weather systems from the north, which often produce cold winter conditions.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] As the fronts between the air masses shift north and south across Alberta, the temperature can change rapidly.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Arctic air masses in the winter produce extreme minimum temperatures varying from −54 °C (−65 °F) in northern Alberta to −46 °C (−51 °F) in southern Alberta, although temperatures at these extremes are rare.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In the summer, continental air masses have produced record maximum temperatures from 32 °C (90 °F) in the mountains to over 40 °C (104 °F) in southeastern Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Annual bright sunshine totals range between 1,900 up to just under 2,600 hours per year.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Northern Alberta gets about 18 hours of daylight in the summer.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The average daytime temperatures range from around 21 °C (70 °F) in the Rocky Mountain valleys and far north, up to around 28 °C (82 °F) in the dry prairie of the southeast.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The northern and western parts of the province experience higher rainfall and lower evaporation rates caused by cooler summer temperatures.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The south and east-central portions are prone to drought-like conditions sometimes persisting for several years, although even these areas can receive heavy precipitation, sometimes resulting in flooding.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In the winter, the Alberta clipper, a type of intense, fast-moving winter storm that generally forms over or near the province and, pushed with great speed by the continental polar jetstream, descends over the rest of southern Canada and the northern tier of the United States.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In southwestern Alberta, the cold winters are frequently interrupted by warm, dry Chinook winds blowing from the mountains, which can propel temperatures upward from frigid conditions to well above the freezing point in a very short period.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] During one Chinook recorded at Pincher Creek, temperatures soared from −19 to 22 °C (−2 to 72 °F) in just one hour.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The region around Lethbridge has the most Chinooks, averaging 30 to 35 Chinook days per year.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Calgary has a 56% chance of a white Christmas, while Edmonton has an 86% chance.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] After Saskatchewan, Alberta experiences the most tornadoes in Canada with an average of 15 verified per year.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Thunderstorms, some of them severe, are frequent in the summer, especially in central and southern Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The region surrounding the Calgary–Edmonton Corridor is notable for having the highest frequency of hail in Canada, which is caused by orographic lifting from the nearby Rocky Mountains, enhancing the updraft/downdraft cycle necessary for the formation of hail.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In central and northern Alberta the arrival of spring is marked by the early flowering of the prairie crocus (*Pulsatilla nuttalliana*) *anemone*; this member of the buttercup family has been recorded flowering as early as March, though April is the usual month for the general population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Other prairie flora known to flower early are the golden bean (*Thermopsis rhombifolia*) and wild rose (*Rosa acicularis*).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Members of the sunflower (*Helianthus*) family blossom on the prairie in the summer months between July and September.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The southern and east central parts of Alberta are covered by short prairie grass, which dries up as summer lengthens, to be replaced by hardy perennials such as the prairie coneflower (*Ratibida*), fleabane, and sage (*Artemisia*).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Both yellow and white sweet clover (*Melilotus*) can be found throughout the southern and central areas of the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The trees in the parkland region of the province grow in clumps and belts on the hillsides.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] These are largely deciduous, typically aspen, poplar, and willow.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Many species of willow and other shrubs grow in virtually any terrain.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] North of the North Saskatchewan River, evergreen forests prevail for thousands of square kilometres.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Aspen poplar, balsam poplar (*Populus balsamifera*) or in some parts cottonwood (*Populus deltoides*), and paper birch (*Betula papyrifera*) are the primary large deciduous species.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Conifers include jack pine (*Pinus banksiana*), Rocky Mountain pine, lodgepole pine (*Pinus contorta*), both white and black spruce, and the deciduous conifer tamarack (*Larix laricina*).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The four climatic regions (alpine, boreal forest, parkland, and prairie) of Alberta are home to many different species of animals.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The south and central prairie was the homeland of the American bison, also known as buffalo, with its grasses providing pasture and breeding ground for millions of buffalo.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The buffalo population was decimated during early settlement, but since then, buffalo have made a comeback, living on farms and in parks all over Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Herbivores are found throughout the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Moose, mule deer, elk, and white-tailed deer are found in the wooded regions, and pronghorn can be found in the prairies of southern Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Bighorn sheep and mountain goats live in the Rocky Mountains.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Rabbits, porcupines, skunks, squirrels, and many species of rodents and reptiles live in every corner of the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta is home to only one venomous snake species, the prairie rattlesnake.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta is home to many large carnivores such as wolves, grizzly bears, black bears, and mountain lions, which are found in the mountains and wooded regions.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Smaller carnivores of the canine and feline families include coyotes, red foxes, Canada lynx, and bobcats.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Wolverines can also be found in the northwestern areas of the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Central and northern Alberta and the region farther north are the nesting ground of many migratory birds.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Vast numbers of ducks, geese, swans and pelicans arrive in Alberta every spring and nest on or near one of the hundreds of small lakes that dot northern Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Eagles, hawks, owls, and crows are plentiful, and a huge variety of smaller seed and insect-eating birds can be found.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta, like other temperate regions, is home to mosquitoes, flies, wasps, and bees.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Rivers and lakes are populated with pike, walleye, whitefish, rainbow, speckled, brown trout, and sturgeon.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Native to the province, the bull trout, is the provincial fish and an official symbol of Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Turtles are found in some water bodies in the southern part of the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Frogs and salamanders are a few of the amphibians that make their homes in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta is the only province in Canada—as well as one of the few places in the world—that is free from Norwegian rats.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Since the early 1950s, the Government of Alberta has operated a rat-control program, which has been so successful that only isolated instances of wild rat sightings are reported, usually of rats arriving in the province aboard trucks or by rail.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 2006, Alberta Agriculture reported zero findings of wild rats; the only rat interceptions have been domesticated rats that have been seized from their owners.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] It is illegal for individual Albertans to own or keep Norwegian rats of any description; the animals can only be kept in the province by zoos, universities and colleges, and recognized research institutions.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 2009, several rats were found and captured, in small pockets in southern Alberta, putting Alberta's rat-free status in jeopardy.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] A colony of rats was subsequently found in a landfill near Medicine Hat in 2012 and again in 2014.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta has one of the greatest diversities and abundances of Late Cretaceous dinosaur fossils worldwide.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Taxa are represented by complete fossil skeletons, isolated material, microvertebrate remains, and even mass graves.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] At least 38 dinosaur type specimens were collected in the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Foremost Formation, Oldman Formation and Dinosaur Park Formations collectively compose the Judith River Group and are the most thoroughly studied dinosaur-bearing strata in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Dinosaur-bearing strata are distributed widely throughout Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Dinosaur Provincial Park area contains outcrops of the Dinosaur Park Formation and Oldman Formation.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In Alberta's central and southern regions are intermittent Scollard Formation outcrops.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In the Drumheller Valley and Edmonton regions there are exposed Horseshoe Canyon facies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Other formations have been recorded as well, like the Milk River and Foremost Formations.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The latter two have a lower diversity of documented dinosaurs, primarily due to their lower total fossil quantity and neglect from collectors who are hindered by the isolation and scarcity of exposed outcrops.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Their dinosaur fossils are primarily teeth recovered from microvertebrate fossil sites.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Additional geologic formations that have produced only a few fossils are the Belly River Group and St.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Mary River Formations of the southwest and the northwestern Wapiti Formation, which contains two *Pachyrhinosaurus* bone beds.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Bearpaw Formation represents strata deposited during a marine transgression.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Dinosaurs are known from this formation, but represent specimens washed out to sea or reworked from older sediments.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Paleo-Indians arrived in what is now Alberta at least 10,000 years ago, toward the end of the last ice age.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] They are thought to have migrated from Siberia to Alaska on a land bridge across the Bering Strait and then possibly moved south along the east side of the Rocky Mountains through Alberta, settling along the way or moving on to settle other parts of the Americas.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Others may have travelled south along the west coast and then moved inland.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The first Europeans to visit Alberta were French Canadian fur traders in the early 18th century.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The first British subject to visit Alberta was Anthony Henday, in 1754.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] French Canadians integrated with local First Nations creating the Metis nation, with elements across the Prairies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] French was the predominant European language in Alberta and was used in some early fur trading forts in the region, such as the first Fort Edmonton (in present-day Fort Saskatchewan), operated by the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] After the British arrival in Canada, approximately half of Alberta's current territory, south of the Athabasca River drainage, became part of Rupert's Land, which consisted of all land drained by rivers flowing into Hudson Bay.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] This area was granted by King Charles II of England to the Hudson's Bay Company in 1670, and rival fur trading companies were not allowed to trade in it.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Athabasca River and the rivers north of it were not in HBC territory, because they drained into the Arctic Ocean instead of Hudson Bay.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The north part of Alberta was a prime habitat for fur-bearing animals and was targeted by the HBC and other fur trading companies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The first European explorer of the Athabasca region was fur trader Peter Pond, who learned of the Methye Portage, a convenient route to travel from rivers in the Hudson Bay watershed to rivers north of Rupert's Land.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] He and other Canadian fur traders formed the North West Company (NWC) of Montreal in 1779, to compete with the HBC.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The NWC built posts at many points across the northern part of Alberta territory.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Peter Pond built Fort Athabasca on Lac la Biche in 1778.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Roderick Mackenzie built Fort Chipewyan on Lake Athabasca ten years later in 1788.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] His cousin, Sir Alexander Mackenzie, followed the North Saskatchewan River to its northernmost point near Edmonton, then trekked on foot to the Athabasca River, which he followed downstream to Lake Athabasca.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] It was there he discovered the mighty outflow river that bears his name – the Mackenzie River – which he followed to its outlet in the Arctic Ocean.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Returning to Lake Athabasca, he followed the Peace River upstream and crossed the Rockies, eventually reaching the Pacific Ocean, and so he became the first European to cross the North American continent north of Mexico.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The extreme southernmost portion of Alberta was part of the French (and Spanish) territory of Louisiana, which was sold to the United States in 1803.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In the Treaty of 1818, the portion of the Louisiana territory north of the Forty-Ninth Parallel was ceded to the United Kingdom.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The area was grouped with Rupert's Land to make the North-Western Territory.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Fur trade expanded in the north, but there was intense friction and competition between the rival HBC and NWC.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 1821 the British government forced them to merge to stop the hostilities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] After amalgamation, the Hudson's Bay Company dominated the economy of Alberta until 1870, when HBC control of Rupert's Land was ended and the territory was transferred to the newly federated Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Southern Alberta, Northern Alberta, other parts of the Northland and Rupert's land became Canada's North-West Territories.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] First Nations and representatives of the Crown negotiated the Numbered Treaties, in which the Crown gained title to the land that would later become Alberta, and the Crown committed to the ongoing support of the First Nations and guaranteed their hunting and fishing rights.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The most significant treaties for Alberta are Treaty 6 (1876), Treaty 7 (1877) and Treaty 8 (1899).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The District of Alberta was created as part of the North-West Territories on 8 May 1882.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] As settlement increased, local representatives to the North-West Legislative Assembly and the House of Commons were elected, and senators appointed, to represent Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] After a long campaign for autonomy, on 1 September 1905, the District of Alberta was enlarged and given provincial status, with the election of a Liberal majority with Alexander Cameron Rutherford as the first premier.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] At first the economy was very active, then around 1912, Alberta suffered a recession.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The First World War presented special challenges to the new province as an extraordinary number of working-age men volunteered for active service, leaving relatively few workers to maintain services and production.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Over 50% of Alberta's doctors volunteered for service overseas.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 1918 Albertans experienced the 1918 flu epidemic.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta voters sought innovation, electing a Farmers government in 1921, then the world's first Social Credit government in 1935.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta's economy stayed sluggish, especially during the Depression.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] But discovery of oil at Leduc in 1946 opened a new era of prosperity and wealth for the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] On June 21, 2013, during the 2013 Alberta floods Alberta experienced heavy rainfall that triggered catastrophic flooding throughout much of the southern half of the province along the Bow, Elbow, Highwood and Oldman rivers and tributaries.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] A dozen municipalities in Southern Alberta declared local states of emergency on June 21 as water levels rose and numerous communities were placed under evacuation orders.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 2016, the Fort McMurray wildfire resulted in the largest fire evacuation of residents in Alberta's history, as more than 80,000 people were ordered to evacuate.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Like the rest of the world, Alberta was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic starting in 2020.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The last restrictions were lifted in 2022.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Statistics Canada estimated the province to have a population of 4,931,601 in Q4 of 2024.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Since 2000, Alberta's population has experienced a relatively high rate of growth, mainly because of its burgeoning economy.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Between 2003 and 2004, the province had high birthrates (on par with some larger provinces such as British Columbia), relatively high immigration, and a high rate of interprovincial migration compared to other provinces.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 2016, Alberta continued to have the youngest population among the provinces with a median age of 36.7 years, compared with the national median of 41.2 years.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Also in 2016, Alberta had the smallest proportion of seniors (12.3%) among the provinces and one of the highest population shares of children (19.2%), further contributing to Alberta's young and growing population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] About 81% of the population lives in urban areas and only about 19% in rural areas.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Calgary–Edmonton Corridor is the most urbanized area in the province and is one of the most densely populated areas of Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Many of Alberta's cities and towns have experienced very high rates of growth in recent history.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Additionally, as per the 2016 census, 1,769,500 residents hold a postsecondary certificate, diploma or degree, 895,885 residents have obtained a secondary (high) school diploma or equivalency certificate, and 540,665 residents do not have any certificate, diploma or degree.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The question on knowledge of languages allows for multiple responses.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] As of the 2016 census, English is the most common mother tongue, with 2,991,485 native speakers.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] This is followed by Tagalog, with 99,035 speakers, German, with 80,050 speakers, French, with 72,150 native speakers, and Punjabi, with 68,695 speakers.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The 2006 census found that English, with 2,576,670 native speakers, was the most common mother tongue of Albertans, representing 79.99% of the population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The next most common mother tongues were Chinese with 97,275 native speakers (3.02%), followed by German with 84,505 native speakers (2.62%) and French with 61,225 (1.90%).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The most common aboriginal language is Cree 17,215 (0.53%).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] According to Statistics Canada, Alberta is home to the second-highest proportion (2%) of Francophones in western Canada (after Manitoba).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Despite this, relatively few Albertans claim French as their mother tongue.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Many of Alberta's French-speaking residents live in the central and northwestern regions of the province, after migration from other areas of Canada or descending from Métis.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta has considerable ethnic diversity.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In line with the rest of Canada, many Albertans are descended from immigrants of Western European nations, notably England, Scotland, Ireland, Wales and France, but large numbers later came from other regions of Europe, notably Germany, Ukraine and Scandinavia.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] More recently, Africans, Asians and South Americans in larger numbers have also contributed to Alberta's ethnic origins.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Many Alberta families today can trace their ethnicity in many directions.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Amongst those of British heritage, the Scots have had a particularly strong influence on place-names.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Many cities and towns have names of Scottish origins, such as Calgary, Airdrie, Canmore, and Banff.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Both Edmonton and Calgary have historic Chinatowns, and Calgary has Canada's third-largest Chinese community.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Chinese presence began with workers employed in the building of the Canadian Pacific Railway in the 1880s.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] In 2021, 27.8% of the population consisted of visible minorities and 6.8% of the population was Indigenous, mostly of First Nations and Métis descent.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] A small number of Inuit live in the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] The Indigenous population has been growing at a faster rate than the population of Alberta as a whole.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Some of this increase is due to Albertans who are only now embracing their Metis lineage.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] As of the 2011 National Household Survey, the largest religious group was Roman Catholic, representing 24.3% of the population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta had the second-highest percentage of non-religious residents among the provinces (after British Columbia) at 31.6% of the population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Of the remainder, 7.5% of the population identified themselves as belonging to the United Church of Canada, while 3.9% were Anglican.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Lutherans made up 3.3% of the population while Baptists constituted 1.9%.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Members of LDS Church are mostly concentrated in the extreme south of the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta has a population of Hutterites, a communal Anabaptist sect similar to the Mennonites, and has a significant population of Seventh-day Adventists.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta is home to several Byzantine Rite Churches as part of the legacy of Eastern European immigration, including the Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Edmonton, and the Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada's Western Diocese which is based in Edmonton.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Muslims made up 3.2% of the population, Sikhs 1.5%, Buddhists 1.2%, and Hindus 1.0%.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Many of these are immigrants, but others have roots that go back to the first settlers of the prairies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Canada's oldest mosque, the Al-Rashid Mosque, is in Edmonton, whereas Calgary is home to Canada's largest mosque, the Baitun Nur Mosque.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Alberta is also home to a growing Jewish population of about 15,400 people who constituted 0.3% of Alberta's population.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p01] Most of Alberta's Jews live in the metropolitan areas of Calgary (8,200) and Edmonton (5,500).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] While most Albertans work in the service sector, Alberta does possess a significant industrial base, intelligence economy and energy sector.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] This energy sector is famously focused in oil and gas extraction.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Oil and gas has been culturally influential, having shaped politics, generated "striking it rich" narratives, and created boom-and-bust cycles.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The majority of Alberta's exports are sent to the United States, and consist of 70% oil and gas, 13% food products, and 12% industrial products.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Before European contact, Indigenous peoples maintained wide trade networks across Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Then, the fur trade, dominated by the Hudson's Bay Company and the North West Company became the region's first major export economy in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Following the transfer of Rupert's Land to Canada in 1870, Alberta's economy transitioned to agriculture and ranching.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The completion of the Canadian Pacific Railway in the 1880s facilitated large-scale settlement and grain exports, particularly wheat, establishing agriculture as the province's new economic backbone.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] A major shift came in 1947 with the discovery of oil near Leduc, launching Alberta's rise as Canada's top oil producer.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] While oil brought prosperity, the 1980s, 2008 and 2014 saw economic setbacks due to price crashes.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Since then, Alberta has worked to diversify its economy, expanding into technology, renewable energy, tourism, and finance to reduce its dependence on oil.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Agriculture employed 35,900 people in 2021, representing roughly 2% of provincial employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Out of them, 19,500 were employed in animal production, 11,800 were employed in crop production, 2,000 were employed in mix farming and 2,600 in support activities or agriculture.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The province has over three million head of cattle, and Alberta beef has a healthy worldwide market.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Forty per cent of all Canadian beef is produced in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The province also produces the most bison meat in Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Sheep for wool and mutton are also raised.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Wheat and canola are primary farm crops, with Alberta leading the provinces in spring wheat production; other grains are also prominent.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Much of the farming is dryland farming, often with fallow seasons interspersed with cultivation.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Continuous cropping (in which there is no fallow season) is gradually becoming a more common mode of production because of increased profits and a reduction of soil erosion.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Across the province, the once common grain elevator is slowly being lost as rail lines are decreasing; farmers typically truck the grain to central points.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2016, forestry provided over 15,000 jobs and generated over $1.0 billion to employment income, $2.6 billion to the provincial GDP, and over $6.1 billion in revenue.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Uses for harvested timber include pulpwood, hardwood, engineered wood and bioproducts such as chemicals and biofuels.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Hybrid canola also requires bee pollination, and some beekeepers service this need.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The mining and quarrying sector, excluding oil and gas, employed approximately 4,300 Albertans in 2021 (around 0.2% of the population) and focused on the mining of coal and mineral resources, such as sand, gravel, salt, limestone, clay, shale and more.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Oil and gas extraction itself however is Alberta's largest and most economically dominant primary industry.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2021, the industry employed roughly 84,500 people in extraction, with another 50,500 in support activities—totaling approximately 135,000 jobs or about 5.6% of Alberta's total employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In terms of economic output, the sector accounted for approximately 27% of Alberta's GDP in 2022.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta also produced about 4.3 million barrels (680,000 m3) of crude oil per day in 2023, making up 84% of Canada's total oil production.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta is the largest producer of conventional crude oil, synthetic crude, natural gas and gas products in Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta is the world's second-largest exporter of natural gas and the fourth-largest producer.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Two of the largest producers of petrochemicals in North America are in central and north-central Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In both Red Deer and Edmonton, polyethylene and vinyl manufacturers produce products that are shipped all over the world.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Edmonton's oil refineries provide the raw materials for a large petrochemical industry to the east of Edmonton.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Athabasca oil sands surrounding Fort McMurray have estimated unconventional oil reserves approximately equal to the conventional oil reserves of the rest of the world, estimated to be 1.6 trillion barrels (250 km3).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Many companies employ both conventional strip mining and non-conventional in situ methods to extract the bitumen from the oil sands.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Another factor determining the viability of oil extraction from the oil sands is the price of oil.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The oil price increases since 2003 have made it profitable to extract this oil, which in the past would give little profit or even a loss.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] By mid-2014, rising costs and stabilizing oil prices threatened the economic viability of some projects.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] An example of this was the shelving of the Joslyn North project in the Athabasca region in May 2014.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] With concerted effort and support from the provincial government, several high-tech industries have found their birth in Alberta, notably patents related to interactive liquid-crystal display systems.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] While not as important as its service sector or as influential as its oil and gas industry, Alberta's secondary sector — comprising manufacturing, construction, and utilities — is still of importance, especially to employment and economic diversification.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2021, Alberta's manufacturing sector employed approximately 122,300 individuals, accounting for 5% of the province's total employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The sector also contributed $23.4 billion, or 8%, to Alberta's Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Key subsectors include food manufacturing (15.8% of manufacturing employment), fabricated metal products (13.6%), machinery (9.8%), wood products (9.8%), and chemicals (8.7%).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Notably, 96% of these jobs were full-time, and 73% of the workforce fell within the core working age of 25–54.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] However, with 20% of workers aged 55 and older, the sector faces impending retirements that could lead to significant job vacancies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's construction industry is a major employer, with 222,200 individuals working in the sector in 2021, representing 10% of the province's workforce.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The industry contributed $23.6 billion to Alberta's GDP, equating to 8% of the total.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Employment is distributed across trade contracting (54.8%), building construction (30.8%), and heavy and civil engineering construction (14.4%).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The workforce is predominantly male (84%), with a significant portion (27%) being self-employed.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Additionally, Indigenous workers constitute 13.5% of the construction labor force, surpassing their representation in the overall provincial workforce.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The utilities sector, which encompasses electricity generation, transmission, and distribution, employed 13,354 Albertans in 2022.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Employment here grew at an average annual rate of 2.6% between 2017 and 2022, largely because of the expansion of renewable energy sources.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's service sector employs around 80% of Albertans, in various fields like retail, healthcare, education, professional services, tourism, FIRE (finance, investment and real estate), transportation and warehousing, food services, public administration, arts and recreation, and more.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Therefore, it unsurprisingly accounts for the majority of Alberta's economic activity.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The retail and wholesale trade sector is a significant employer in Alberta, accounting for approximately 15% of total provincial employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2022, wholesale trade contributed $14.7 billion, and retail trade contributed $14.1 billion to Alberta's GDP, collectively making up about 8% of the province's total GDP.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Healthcare and social assistance, which includes hospitals, clinics, nursing homes and community health programs, is similarly one of the largest employers in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2020, approximately 247,100 individuals were employed in this sector, representing about 11% of the province's total employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] About 88,800 of these jobs are in the ambulatory health care services sub-sector, while 107,800 are employed in the hospitals sub-sector and 50,500 are employed in nursing and residential care facilities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In terms of economic contribution, the sector added $16.7 billion to Alberta's GDP in 2020, accounting for 5.4% of the provincial total.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Employment prospects here are good, due to an aging population and ongoing labor shortages, particularly in nursing and residential care facilities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Educational services account for 7.1% of total provincial employment in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2022, of the 168,100 people employed here, about 98,400 people (58.5%) worked in primary and secondary education, 36,400 people (21.7%) worked in university education, 17,800 (10.6%) worked in other schools and educational support, and 12,200 (7.3%) worked in post-secondary education.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2022, the sector contributed $12.4 billion, or 4%, to the provincial GDP.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The finance, insurance, real estate and leasing (or FIRE) is a big part of Alberta's economy.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2023, the finance and insurance sector alone contributed $14.88 billion to the province's GDP, with a five-year average growth rate of 2.8%.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In February 2025, activity in this sub-sector declined for the third consecutive month, reflecting a cooling in home resale activity across the country.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The professional, scientific, and technical services sector has experienced rapid growth in recent times, with employment increasing by 28,700 jobs (15.1%) between 2021 and 2022.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Since 2018, employment has grown by 47,300 jobs (27.6%), making it one of the fastest-growing sectors in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The transportation and warehousing sector employed 130,900 people in 2021, accounting for 6% of total provincial employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Employment in this sector increased by 10,600 jobs (8.8%) from 2020 to 2021.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2022, approximately 108,200 people were employed in Alberta's public administration sector, accounting for 4.6% of provincial employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Employment in this sector increased by 5,000 jobs (4.8%) from 2021 to 2022.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The arts, entertainment, and recreation sector contributed $1.61 billion to Alberta's GDP in 2023, with an 8.2% growth.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] However, over a five-year period, the sector experienced an annualized -3.7% GDP and -3.5% employment decline, despite employing 22,663 people in 2023.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] This may be due to COVID-19 pandemic-related disruptions, but lower funding from government, higher difficulty in obtaining and retaining staff, and shifts in consumer behaviour could also be contributing factors.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The accommodation and food services -which encompasses accommodations, food and beverage services, recreation and entertainment, and travel services- is a significant component of Alberta's service economy.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] 140,400 people were employed here in 2023, which accounts for 6.1% of Alberta's total employment.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Furthermore, in 2023, the sector contributed approximately $8.1 billion to Alberta's GDP, marking a 7.8% increase from the previous year.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] This growth indicates a strong recovery from the pandemic's impact, with the sector surpassing pre-pandemic levels for the first time.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] According to Alberta Economic Development, Calgary and Edmonton both host over four million visitors annually.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Banff, Jasper and the Rocky Mountains are visited by about three million people per year.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta tourism relies heavily on Southern Ontario tourists, as well as tourists from other parts of Canada, the United States, and many other countries.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] There are also natural attractions like Elk Island National Park, Wood Buffalo National Park, and the Columbia Icefield.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's Rockies include well-known tourist destinations Banff National Park and Jasper National Park.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The two mountain parks are connected by the scenic Icefields Parkway.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Banff is located 128 km (80 mi) west of Calgary on Highway 1, and Jasper is located 366 km (227 mi) west of Edmonton on the Yellowhead Highway.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Five of Canada's fourteen UNESCO World Heritage Sites are located within the province: Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park, Wood Buffalo National Park, Dinosaur Provincial Park and Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] A number of these areas hold ski resorts, most notably Banff Sunshine, Lake Louise, Marmot Basin, Norquay and Nakiska.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] About 1.2 million people visit the Calgary Stampede, a celebration of Canada's own Wild West and the cattle ranching industry.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] About 700,000 people enjoy Edmonton's K-Days (formerly Klondike Days and Capital EX).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Edmonton was the gateway to the only all-Canadian route to the Yukon gold fields, and the only route which did not require gold-seekers to travel the exhausting and dangerous Chilkoot Pass.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Another tourist destination that draws more than 650,000 visitors each year is the Drumheller Valley, located northeast of Calgary.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Drumheller, known as the "Dinosaur Capital of The World", offers the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Drumheller also had a rich mining history being one of Western Canada's largest coal producers during the war years.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Another attraction in east-central Alberta is Alberta Prairie Railway Excursions, a popular tourist attraction operated out of Stettler, that offers train excursions into the prairie and caters to tens of thousands of visitors every year.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Government of Alberta is organized as a parliamentary democracy with a unicameral legislature.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Its unicameral legislature—the Legislative Assembly—consists of 87 members elected first past the post (FPTP) from single-member constituencies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Locally municipal governments and school boards are elected and operate separately.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Their boundaries do not necessarily coincide.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] As King of Canada, Charles III is the head of state of Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] His duties concerning the Government of Alberta are carried out by Lieutenant Governor Salma Lakhani.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The King and lieutenant governor are figureheads whose actions are highly restricted by custom and constitutional convention.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The lieutenant governor handles numerous honorific duties in the name of the King.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The government is headed by the premier.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The premier is normally a member of the Legislative Assembly, and draws all the members of the Cabinet from among the members of the Legislative Assembly.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The City of Edmonton is the seat of the provincial government—the capital of Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The current premier is Danielle Smith, who was sworn in on October 11, 2022.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's elections have tended to yield much more conservative outcomes than those of other Canadian provinces.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] From the 1980s to the 2010s, Alberta had three main political parties, the Progressive Conservatives ("Conservatives" or "Tories"), the Liberals, and the social democratic New Democrats.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The strongly conservative Social Credit Party was a power in Alberta for many decades, but fell from the political map after the Progressive Conservatives came to power in 1971.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] For 44 years the Progressive Conservatives governed Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] All types of municipalities are governed by local residents and were incorporated under various provincial acts, with the exception of improvement districts (governed by either the provincial or federal government), and Indian reserves (governed by local band governments under federal jurisdiction).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Policing in the province of Alberta upon its creation was the responsibility of the Royal Northwest Mounted Police.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 1917, due to pressures of the First World War, the Alberta Provincial Police was created.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] This organization policed the province until it was disbanded as a Great Depression-era cost-cutting measure in 1932.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] It was at that time the, now renamed, Royal Canadian Mounted Police resumed policing of the province, specifically RCMP "K" Division.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] With the advent of the Alberta Sheriffs Branch, the distribution of duties of law enforcement in Alberta has been evolving as certain aspects, such as traffic enforcement, mobile surveillance and the close protection of the Premier of Alberta have been transferred to the Sheriffs.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2006, Alberta formed the Alberta Law Enforcement Response Teams (ALERT) to combat organized crime and the serious offences that accompany it.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] ALERT is made up of members of the RCMP, Sheriffs Branch, and various major municipal police forces in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Military bases in Alberta include Canadian Forces Base (CFB) Cold Lake, CFB Edmonton, CFB Suffield and CFB Wainwright.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Air force units stationed at CFB Cold Lake have access to the Cold Lake Air Weapons Range.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] CFB Edmonton is the headquarters for the 3rd Canadian Division.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] CFB Suffield hosts British troops and is the largest training facility in Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] According to Alberta's 2009 budget, government revenue in that year came mainly from royalties on non-renewable natural resources (30.4%), personal income taxes (22.3%), corporate and other taxes (19.6%), and grants from the federal government primarily for infrastructure projects (9.8%).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2014, Alberta received $6.1 billion in bitumen royalties.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] With the drop in the price of oil in 2015 it was down to $1.4 billion.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2016, Alberta received "about $837 million in royalty payments from oil sands Royalty Projects".
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] According to the 2018–2021 fiscal plan, the two top sources of revenue in 2016 were personal income tax at $10,763 million and federal transfers of $7,976 million with total resource revenue at $3,097 million.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta is the only province in Canada without a provincial sales tax.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta residents are subject to the federal sales tax, the Goods and Services Tax of 5%.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] From 2001 to 2016, Alberta was the only Canadian province to have a flat tax of 10% of taxable income, which was introduced by Premier, Ralph Klein, as part of the Alberta Tax Advantage, which also included a zero-per cent tax on income below a "generous personal exemption".
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2016, under Premier Rachel Notley, while most Albertans continued to pay the 10% income tax rate, new tax brackets 12%, 14%, and 15% for those with higher incomes ($128,145 annually or more) were introduced.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's personal income tax system maintained a progressive character by continuing to grant residents personal tax exemptions of $18,451, in addition to a variety of tax deductions for persons with disabilities, students, and the aged.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's municipalities and school jurisdictions have their own governments who usually work in co-operation with the provincial government.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] By 2018, most Albertans continued to pay the 10% income tax rate.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] According to a March 2015 Statistics Canada report, the median household income in Alberta in 2014 was about $100,000, which is 23% higher than the Canadian national average.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Based on Statistic Canada reports, low-income Albertans, who earn less than $25,000 and those in the high-income bracket earning $150,000 or more, are the lowest-taxed people in Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Those in the middle income brackets representing those that earn about $25,000 to $75,000 pay more in provincial taxes than residents in British Columbia and Ontario.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In terms of income tax, Alberta is the "best province" for those with a low income because there is no provincial income tax for those who earn $18,915 or less.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Even with the 2016 progressive tax brackets up to 15%, Albertans who have the highest incomes, those with a $150,000 annual income or more—about 178,000 people in 2015, pay the least in taxes in Canada. — About 1.9 million Albertans earned between $25,000 and $150,000 in 2015.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta also privatized alcohol distribution.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] By 2010, privatization had increased outlets from 304 stores to 1,726; 1,300 jobs to 4,000 jobs; and 3,325 products to 16,495 products.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Tax revenue also increased from $400 million to $700 million.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2017/18 Alberta collected about $2.4 billion in education property taxes from municipalities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta municipalities raise a significant portion of their income through levying property taxes.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The value of assessed property in Alberta was approximately $727 billion in 2011.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Most real property is assessed according to its market value.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The exceptions to market value assessment are farmland, railways, machinery and equipment and linear property, all of which is assessed by regulated rates.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Depending on the property type, property owners may appeal a property assessment to their municipal 'Local Assessment Review Board', 'Composite Assessment Review Board,' or the Alberta Municipal Government Board.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Calgary is famous for its Stampede, dubbed "The Greatest Outdoor Show on Earth".
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Stampede is Canada's biggest rodeo festival and features various races and competitions, such as calf roping and bull riding.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In line with the western tradition of rodeo are the cultural artisans that reside and create unique Alberta western heritage crafts.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Summer brings many festivals to Alberta, especially in Edmonton.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Edmonton Fringe Festival is the world's second-largest after the Edinburgh Festival.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Both Calgary and Edmonton host many annual festivals and events, including folk music festivals.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The city's "heritage days" festival sees the participation of over 70 ethnic groups.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Edmonton's Churchill Square is home to a large number of the festivals, including A Taste of Edmonton and The Works Art & Design Festival throughout the summer months.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The award comes with $60,000 funding which includes travel and materials costs.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] On January 31, 2019, Lauren Crazybull was named Alberta's first artist in residence.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta is the first province to launch an artist in residence program in Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] As with any Canadian province, the Alberta Legislature has (almost) exclusive authority to make laws respecting education.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] There are forty-two public school jurisdictions in Alberta, and seventeen operating separate school jurisdictions.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Sixteen of the operating separate school jurisdictions have a Catholic electorate, and one (St.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In addition, one Protestant separate school district, Glen Avon, survives as a ward of the St.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The City of Lloydminster straddles the Albertan/Saskatchewan border, and both the public and separate school systems in that city are counted in the above numbers: both of them operate according to Saskatchewan law.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] For many years, the provincial government has funded the greater part of the cost of providing K–12 education.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Prior to 1994, public and separate school boards in Alberta had the legislative authority to levy a local tax on property as supplementary support for local education.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 1994, the government of the province eliminated this right for public school boards, but not for separate school boards.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Since 1994, there has continued to be a tax on property in support of K–12 education; the difference is that the provincial government now sets the mill rate, the money is collected by the local municipal authority and remitted to the provincial government.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The relevant legislation requires that all the money raised by this property tax must go to support K–12 education provided by school boards.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The provincial government pools the property tax funds from across the province and distributes them, according to a formula, to public and separate school jurisdictions and Francophone authorities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Public and separate school boards, charter schools, and private schools all follow the Program of Studies and the curriculum approved by the provincial department of education (Alberta Education).
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Homeschool tutors may choose to follow the Program of Studies or develop their own Program of Studies.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Several publicly funded post-secondary institutions are governed under the province's *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Nine comprehensive community colleges offer primarily offer diploma and certificate programs, Bow Valley College, Keyano College, Lakeland College, Lethbridge College, Medicine Hat College, NorQuest College, Northern Lakes College, Olds College, and Portage College.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In addition, there are also four polytechnic institutes that provide specific career training and provides apprenticeships and diplomas, the Northern Alberta Institute of Technology, the Southern Alberta Institute of Technology, Northwestern Polytechnic, and Red Deer Polytechnic.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity is a specialized arts and cultural institution that is also empowered to provide diploma programs under the *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta is also home to five independent postsecondary institutions that provide diplomas/degrees for approved programming, Ambrose University, Burman University, Concordia University of Edmonton, The King's University, and St.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Although the five institutions operate under their own legislation, they remain partly governed by the province's *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In addition to these institutions, there are also 190 private career colleges in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta provides a publicly funded, fully integrated health system, through Alberta Health Services (AHS)—a quasi-independent agency that delivers health care on behalf of the Government of Alberta's Ministry of Health.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Alberta government provides health services for all its residents as set out by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta became Canada's second province (after Saskatchewan) to adopt a Tommy Douglas-style program in 1950, a precursor to the modern medicare system.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta's health care budget was $22.5 billion during the 2018–2019 fiscal year (approximately 45% of all government spending), making it the best-funded health-care system per-capita in Canada.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Every hour the province spends more than $2.5 million, (or $60 million per day), to maintain and improve health care in the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Edmonton Clinic complex, completed in 2012, provides a similar research, education, and care environment as the Mayo Clinic in the United States.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] All public health care services funded by the Government of Alberta are delivered operationally by Alberta Health Services.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] AHS is the province's single health authority, established on July 1, 2008, which replaced nine regional health authorities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] AHS also funds all ground ambulance services in the province, as well as the province-wide Shock Trauma Air Rescue Service (STARS) air ambulance service.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta is well-connected by air, with international airports in both Calgary and Edmonton.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Calgary International Airport and Edmonton International Airport are the fourth- and fifth-busiest in Canada, respectively.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Edmonton's airport acts as a hub for the Canadian north and has connections to all major Canadian airports as well as airports in the United States, Europe, Mexico, and the Caribbean .
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Calgary, Edmonton, Red Deer, Medicine Hat, and Lethbridge have substantial public transit systems.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In addition to buses, Calgary and Edmonton operate light rail transit (LRT) systems.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Edmonton LRT, which is underground in the downtown core and on the surface outside the downtown core was the first of the modern generation of light rail systems to be built in North America, while the Calgary CTrain has one of the highest numbers of daily riders of any LRT system in North America.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] There are more than 9,000 km (5,600 mi) of operating mainline railway in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The vast majority of this trackage is owned by the Canadian Pacific Kansas City (CPKC) and Canadian National Railway (CN) companies, which operate freight transport across the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Additional railfreight service in the province is provided by two shortline railways: the Battle River Railway and Forty Mile Rail.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Passenger trains include Via Rail's *Canadian* (Toronto–Vancouver) and Jasper–Prince Rupert trains, which use the CN mainline and pass through Jasper National Park and parallel the Yellowhead Highway during at least part of their routes.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The Rocky Mountaineer operates two sections: one from Vancouver to Banff over CP tracks, and a section that travels over CN tracks to Jasper.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] In 2024 Alberta's premier, Danielle Smith, announced a 15-year master plan to expand passenger rail in Alberta.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] This plan envisions rail services to Lethbridge, Medicine Hat, Banff, Grande Prairie, Fort McMurray, and most importantly an intercity rail service between Edmonton and Calgary, as well as commuter rail systems in the respective cities.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Ground-breaking was planned for 2027, according to Transportation Minister Devin Dreeshen.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta has over 473,000 km (294,000 mi) of highways and roads in its road network.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The main north–south corridor is Highway 2, which begins south of Cardston at the Carway border crossing and is part of the CANAMEX Corridor.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Beginning at the Coutts border crossing and ending at Lethbridge, Highway 4, effectively extends Interstate 15 into Alberta and is the busiest United States gateway to the province.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Highway 3 joins Lethbridge to Fort Macleod and links Highway 2 to Highway 4.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Highway 2 travels north through Fort Macleod, Calgary, Red Deer, and Edmonton.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] North of Edmonton, the highway continues to Athabasca, then northwesterly along the south shore of Lesser Slave Lake into High Prairie, north to Peace River, west to Fairview and finally south to Grande Prairie, where it ends at an interchange with Highway 43.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The section of Highway 2 between Calgary and Edmonton has been named the Queen Elizabeth II Highway to commemorate the visit of the monarch in 2005.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Highway 2 is supplemented by two more highways that run parallel to it: Highway 22, west of Highway 2, known as *Cowboy Trail*, and Highway 21, east of Highway 2.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Highway 43 travels northwest into Grande Prairie and the Peace River Country.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Travelling northeast from Edmonton, the Highway 63 connects to Fort McMurray and the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Alberta has two main east–west corridors.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The southern corridor, part of the Trans-Canada Highway system, enters the province near Medicine Hat, runs westward through Calgary, and leaves Alberta through Banff National Park.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The northern corridor, also part of the Trans-Canada network and known as the Yellowhead Highway (Highway 16), runs west from Lloydminster in eastern Alberta, through Edmonton and Jasper National Park into British Columbia.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] One of the most scenic drives is along the Icefields Parkway, which runs for 228 km (142 mi) between Jasper and Lake Louise, with mountain ranges and glaciers on either side of its entire length.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] A third corridor stretches across southern Alberta; Highway 3 runs between Crowsnest Pass and Medicine Hat through Lethbridge and forms the eastern portion of the Crowsnest Highway.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Another major corridor through central Alberta is Highway 11 (also known as the David Thompson Highway), which runs east from the Saskatchewan River Crossing in Banff National Park through Rocky Mountain House and Red Deer, connecting with Highway 12, 20 km (12 mi) west of Stettler.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] The highway connects many of the smaller towns in central Alberta with Calgary and Edmonton, as it crosses Highway 2 just west of Red Deer.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Urban stretches of Alberta's major highways and freeways are often called *trails*.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] For example, Highway 2, the main north–south highway in the province, is called Deerfoot Trail as it passes through Calgary but becomes Calgary Trail (southbound) and Gateway Boulevard (northbound) as it enters Edmonton and then turns into St.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Albert Trail as it leaves Edmonton for the City of St.
[src:akvavit/alberta-p02] Calgary, in particular, has a tradition of calling its largest urban expressways *trails* and naming many of them after prominent First Nations individuals and tribes, such as Crowchild Trail, Deerfoot Trail, and Stoney Trail.
